observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our previous years’ recommendations that:
· The Inventory Committee conduct complete inventory taking of all the Municipal properties and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and the Report of Unserviceable Property for submission to the Municipal Accountant and Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of every year;
· The General Services Officer submit to the Municipal Accountant the set of papers pertaining to the disposal of unserviceable properties for eventual preparation of journal entry voucher as basis of deduction from the PPE account;
· The General Services Officer in coordination with the created Inventory Committee reconcile Inventory Report and Property records with that of the Accounting records. Exert extra efforts to identify/account the properties acquired prior to 2002 in lump sum amount based on available records of both offices. Require person responsible/accountable to request for relief from accountability to the Commission Proper for those properties that are missing and could not be accounted for; and
· The Municipal Accountant and the GSO/Property Officer maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, to facilitate the reconciliation of both records.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a) Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer exert more effort to reconcile the balances of RPT and SET Receivables. Prepare Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) for the necessary adjusting entries to reflect the accurate balances of the accounts as of the accounting period;
b) Direct the Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Administrator, and Municipal Assessor to coordinate and jointly exert extra efforts in the collection of delinquent accounts and adopt necessary measures to enable the maximum collection of unpaid taxes;
c) Require the Municipal Treasurer to submit the Certified List of all Real Property Tax Delinquencies to the Sangguniang Bayan on or before the 31st of December of the year immediately succeeding the year in which the delinquencies were incurred, with the request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection therein. Also, coordinate with the Office of the Provincial Treasurer for more issuance of Warrant of Levy;
d) Ensure that the Sangguniang Bayan enact ordinance that will enhance collection scheme, encourage taxpayers to pay their taxes and impose additional penalties or incentives to promote sound collection system as provided on existing provisions of the Local Government Code; and
e) Maximize availment of all legal and administrative remedies either by administrative action through levy on real property or judicial action.

We reiterated our previous years’ recommendations that:
The Inventory Committee conduct complete inventory taking of all the Municipal properties particularly on those not included in the last year and  prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and the Report of Unserviceable Property for submission to the Municipal Accountant and Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of every year;
The General Services Officer submit to the Municipal Accountant the set of papers pertaining to the disposal of unserviceable properties for  eventual preparation of journal entry voucher as basis of deduction from the PPE account;
The General Services Officer reconcile Inventory Report and Property records with that of the Accounting records. Exert extra efforts to identify/account the properties acquired prior to 2002 in lump sum amount based on available records of both offices.  Require person responsible/accountable to request for relief from accountability to the Commission Proper for those properties that are missing and could not be accounted for; and
The Municipal Accountant and the GSO/Property Officer maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, to facilitate the reconciliation of both records.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Direct the Municipal  Treasurer,   Municipal Administrator, and Municipal Assessor to coordinate and jointly  exert extra efforts in the collection of delinquent accounts and adopt necessary measures to enable the maximum collection of unpaid taxes;
Instruct the Municipal Administrator and Human Resource Management Officer   to maximize the utilization of the manpower resources and make transportation available to facilitate tax collection and campaign procedures as well as distribution of Notice of Delinquencies to various delinquent taxpayers in the 42 barangays of the Municipality;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to submit the Certified  List of  all Real Property Tax Delinquencies  to the  Sangguniang Bayan on or before the 31st of December of the year immediately  succeeding the year in which the delinquencies were incurred, with the request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection therein.  Also, coordinate with the Office of the Provincial Treasurer for more issuance of Warrant of Levy;
Ensure that the  Sangguniang Bayan enact ordinance that will enhance collection scheme, encourage taxpayers to pay their taxes and impose additional penalties or incentives to promote sound collection system as provided on existing provisions of the Local Government Code; and
Maximize availment  of all legal and administrative remedies either by administrative action through levy on real property or judicial action.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Adopt and enforce appropriate issuances to institutionalize the establishment of GFPS;
Require the MPDC to spearhead the setting up  and  maintenance  of  the  GAD  database;
Create the LGU GFPS or its TWG who will
provide technical assistance to the MPDC in ensuring that the GAD Database is operational;
Submit GAD Plan and Budget to the Provincial Planning and Development Office to ensure GAD PPAs alignment to the priorities of the province and make sure that it will be reviewed and approved by the DILG Regional Office;
-   Ensure mainstreaming of GAD concerns in the local development   plans;
Remind the Sangguniang Bayan to take the necessary actions in order to pass a GAD Code that will support the LGU’s efforts in promoting, protecting and fulfilling  women’s empowerment; and
Ensure the utilization of 5% GAD Budget only on PPAs which address gender issues and concerns, to avoid disallowance in audit.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct  the  Department Heads concerned and the BAC Committee to:
Exercise diligence of a  good father of the family in the procurement planning and execution to ensure that government funds are expended  and  wastage are avoided, through proper fiscal management, with a view to ensuring efficiency, economy and effectiveness in the operation of the government.;
Conduct consultation, study and evaluation of a specific project or program with an end view of considering the feasibility, practicability and effectiveness of the project towards its end-users and the cost of public funds to be expended for the purpose;
Require the MENRO Head to submit justification on why the facilities procured were not properly utilized and maintained by the recipients and likewise not monitored by the Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Office, thus, resulted in  non-effectiveness of the program and the wastage of government fund.;
Submit justification why another procurement was made inspite audit observations and recommendation in the previous Annual Audit 
Report; and
Immediately furnish the Audit Team the lacking documents required by the COA Technical Audit Specialist as stated above.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Direct the MENRO to exert more efforts for the approval of the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan and its implementation;
Take appropriate  action for establishment of  the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board;
Strictly implement the “No Segregation, No Collection Policy” and pass ordinance that will prohibit the use of plastic bags in groceries, restaurants and other establishments and providing penalties for violations thereof; utilize all  the job orders that are charged under the Solid Waste Management Program;
Provide justification for the incurrence of a total P3,511,234.00  for the rental of heavy equipment since the Municipality already owned a bulldozer stationed in the dumpsite with 2 assigned bulldozer operators;
Expedite the repair of dump truck to avoid incurrence of rental expense for a similar truck; and
Strictly implement and cause the immediate and effective rehabilitation of the dumpsite, and work on the Municipality’s Action Plan for its closure; the  Municipality   consider and allocate budget for the purchase of Land for alternative dumpsite  while in process of the rehabilitation and closure of the present dumpsite,  and eventually the construction and  maintenance  of sanitary landfill  in accordance with RA 9003.
